         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                            <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                        </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               <add>Speaking of the increase of <unclear>herceivy</unclear>
               </add>
               <add>(Wh some ascribe to Harrison)</add>
                    Neither do I speak this reproach of any man as <del>every</del>
               <del>man</del> God is my judge, but rather I do rejoice to see how God
                    <del>&amp; be</del> has blest us with his good gifts and <del>enabled</del> to behold
                    how that in a time Where all things are grown to such ex
                    cessive prices we do yet find the mean to obtain &amp; admire
                    such furniture as heretofore has <add>been</add>
               <unclear>found impossible</unclear>: There 
                    are <unclear>old men? women?</unclear> yet dwelling in the village where I remain
                    which have noted 3 things to be marvellously altered in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName>
                    within their sound remembrance -
                    One is the multitude of chimnies lately created whereas
                    in their young days there were but two or three of so small
                    in most uplandish towns of the realm - the religious house,
                    and manor houses of their Lords always excepted &amp; peradven
                    ture some great personage ) But each made his <unclear>fire</unclear>by <unclear>means of</unclear>
                    a <unclear>rere dosse</unclear> in the hall, Where he dined and <unclear>dressed</unclear> his meat
                    The 2<hi rend="superscript">nd</hi> is the great amendment in lodging for said <unclear/> your
                    <unclear>father</unclear> and ourselves have lain full of it on straw pallets
                    covered only with a sheet under coverlets of dogs <unclear/> or
                   <unclear>hop</unclear> harlots I use their own terms &amp; a good round log under
                    their head as a bolster) If it were so that the father or goodman
                    of the house had a mattress or feather bed &amp; thereon a sack of
                    chaff to rest his head upon he thought himself as well looked
                    as the lord of the town - Pillows <unclear>said</unclear> they are thought fit only
                    for sick woman as for servants if they had any sheet above them
                    
                    
                   <unclear/> well for seldom had they any <unclear>under their</unclear>bodies
                    to keep them from the pricking straws that <unclear>raise</unclear> oft through
                    the <unclear>canvas</unclear> &amp; <unclear>rare</unclear> other hardened<unclear/>
                    the 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> thing they tell of is the exchange of <unclear/> platters
                    (so called from tree wood) into pewter &amp; wooden spoons into
                    silver or tin - for so common were all sorts of <unclear/>
                    vessels in <unclear>those times</unclear> that a man could hardly find
                    4 pieces of pewter of which <unclear>one was</unclear> peradventure
                    was a Salt- ) in a good farm house
                    Hollingshead prefixed to his
                    history - <add>wh</add> some <del>suppose</del>
                    ascribed to <unclear>Harrison</unclear>
                    Autograph of Maria Edgeworth
                    obtained from Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>Beaufort
                    Dear Lovell
                    Now that we hope
                    you are recovering from y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
            </p>
